3 Results

3.1 Overall

There were 47 different species recorded across the 5 years with data. The most common species was New Holland Honeyeater with 235 records.

Zero species appeared to increase over the years of the study, while zero species showed a decrease.

The table below shows the:

  • species recorded
  • total number of records for a species
  • number of years in which a species was recorded; and
  • the number of cells in which a species was recorded
  • guestimate of trend for the species, based on a linear model fitted to the number of cells by year

Each cell was 50 by 50 metres.

Below the table is a map showing where all records were taken.


3.2 By species

3.2.1 Australian Magpie

There were 112 records of Australian Magpie (Gymnorhina tibicen). Figure 3.1 shows where the records were taken.

Australian Magpie were most frequently recorded in habitat(s) revegetation although they were also recorded in: pasture, remnant and vineyard (see figure 3.2).

The trend in number of cells with a Australian Magpie record was ‘probably stable’ (also see figure 3.3).

There were 48 records of Yellow-faced Honeyeater (Lichenostomus chrysops). Figure 3.115 shows where the records were taken.

Yellow-faced Honeyeater were most frequently recorded in habitat(s) revegetation although they were also recorded in: remnant (see figure 3.116).

The trend in number of cells with a Yellow-faced Honeyeater record was ‘probably stable’ (also see figure 3.117).
